ANTHRAX, HUMAN, LIVESTOCK - BANGLADESH: MORE CASES
**************************************************

A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

[1]
Date: Fri 27 May 2011
Source: bdnews24.com [edited]
http://bdnews24.com/details.php?id=196830&cid=13


16 people, including 3 children, have been found infected with the
bacterium in Shahjadpur upazila in Sirajganj, a couple of weeks after
this year's [2011] 1st outbreak was reported in Sathia, Pabna. Local
health officials say the outbreak took place in Saratail village under
Kayempur union council of the upazila.

Resident physician of Shahjadpur Upazila Complex Dr Abdul Awal told
bdnews24.com that 16 people infected with anthrax were given treatment
at the hospital over the last 3 days.

A 3-member team of the livestock department rushed to the spot on
Friday [27 May 2011], bdnews24.com Sirajganj correspondent reports.

However, the director of the Institute of Epidemiology Disease
Control and Research (IEDCR) that oversees human infection urged
people not to panic, and instead to be aware of the disease. He said
doctors were better trained to manage anthrax infection. The infection
in skin is not life-threatening if detected early.

Prof Mahmudur Rahman strongly recommended "not to slaughter sick
cattle." He said the organism passes on to humans while handling sick
livestock, but person to person transmission does not occur.

Pabna, Sirajganj, Kushtia, Tangail, Meherpur, Manikganj, Satkhira,
Lalmonirhat, Rajshahi, Narayanganj, Laxmipur, and Chittagong are the
anthrax endemic districts. [Actually, these are just districts with
human cases. 15 districts were affected last year (2010) with human
and/or livestock cases. - Mod.MHJ]

Sirajganj Upazila livestock officer Altaf Hossain told bdnews24.com
that a cow was slaughtered in the village on 13 May 2011, and those
who processed the meat and consumed it got infected with anthrax. He
said cattle vaccination was underway in the district. Even a cheap
vaccine can keep animals immune from the bacterium.

Experts suggest coordination between human health and livestock
departments on a "one health approach" to stem such bacterial
zoonoses.

The IEDCR director says people should know how to dispose of dead
animals. They usually throw dead animals either into water bodies or
into open fields. "That helps the bacterium stay on the surface," said
Prof Rahman, and he urged all to bury dead animals after wrapping them
with plastic.

The government officially started reporting human infections of
anthrax in August 2009. The number of total infections was 610 before
the Sirajganj outbreak.

The bacterium can survive in harsh conditions for even centuries in
the soil. Cattle get infected while grazing during the rainy season
when water brings the bacterium to the surface, experts say.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>

[The district affected in this incident has clay soil, which normally
does not aid anthrax spore survival. We have yet to hear back from the
investigation by the joint IEDCR and ICDDR.B on the previous
caprine-based outbreak.

There is a severe problem of rural poverty in Bangladesh, which
results in livestock owners slaughtering moribund animals so that they
can recover something from the event; Muslims are forbidden from
eating meat from animals that had died, but it is permitted to
slaughter and butcher sick animals, thus the ongoing problems. Also,
there is frankly not enough livestock vaccine available to cover the
animals in all 15 affected districts, which should have been
vaccinated in March 2011, not retroactively now. - Mod.MHJ]

